Definition 2.3.7. Let $\Sigma=(\ast,\Sigma_{1},\Sigma_{2},\Sigma_{3})$ be a $3$-polygraph with one $0$-cell. Its associated reduction graph is the graph denoted by $G(\Sigma)$ defined this way: 0. The objects of $G(\Sigma)$ are the $2$-arrows of $\langle\Sigma\rangle_{2}$. 1. The arrows of $G(\Sigma)$ from $u$ to $v$ are all the triples $(f,\alpha,g)$, made of two $2$-arrows $f$ and $g$ of $\langle\Sigma\rangle_{2}$ and one $3$-cell $\alpha$ of $\Sigma_{3}$, such that the following two equalities are defined and hold: $t_{2}\alpha$$f$$f$$g$$g$$=$$u$$=$$v$$s_{2}\alpha$ Each triple $(f,\alpha,g)$ is represented by the following diagram: $\alpha$$f$$g$ The triples are considered modulo the following deformation equations, given for every possible $2$-arrows $f$, $g$ and $h$ and $3$-cell $\alpha$: $\alpha$$=$$=$$f$$f$$f$$f$$g$$g$$h$$h$$h$$h$$g$$g$$\alpha$$\alpha$$\alpha$
Definition A.2. Let $h$ be a functor from $\mathcal{K}$ to the category of sets. The functor $h$ is said to satisfy the colimit axiom if for all relative $I$-cell complexes $A\rightarrow X$ $\text{colim}_{\alpha}\,h(X_{\alpha})\rightarrow h(X)$ is a bijection where the colimit is over all relative sub $I$-cell complexes $i_{\alpha}\colon A\rightarrow X_{\alpha}$ of $i$ such that $\sharp(X_{\alpha},A)$ is finite.
Definition 4.7. Let $A$ be a monoid in $\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$, i.e. $A$ is a differential graded $R$-algebra. Denote the category of $A$-modules in $\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$ by $A$-$\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$.
Definition 7.1. The class of (co-)$n$-equivalences in $\mathcal{K}$ is the class of maps $f$ in $\mathcal{K}$ such that the homotopy type of $\text{hofib}(f)$ is in $\text{Ho}(\mathcal{K})_{\geq n}$ ($\text{Ho}(\mathcal{K})_{\leq n-1}$) [8, 3.1].
Definition 2.1. Let $\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$ denote the category of chain complexes of presheaves of $iR$-modules on $\mathcal{C}$, and let $\text{ch}(\mathcal{M})$ denote the category of chain complexes of sheaves of $R$-modules on $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $i_{C,n}$ be the map of chain complexes $\xymatrix{\cdots\ar[r]\ar[d]&0\ar[r]\ar[d]&0\ar[r]\ar[d]&R_{C}\ar[d]^{=}\ar[r]% &0\ar[r]\ar[d]&\cdots\ar[d]\\ \cdots\ar[r]&0\ar[r]&R_{C}\ar[r]^{=}&R_{C}\ar[r]&0\ar[r]&\cdots}$ where $C\in\mathcal{C}$ and the vertical identity map on $R_{C}$ is in degree $n$. Let $I$ be the set of all $i_{C,n}$ for $C\in\mathcal{C}$ and $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. Let $j_{C,n}$ be the map of chain complexes $\xymatrix{\cdots\ar[r]\ar[d]&0\ar[r]\ar[d]&0\ar[r]\ar[d]&0\ar[d]\ar[r]&0\ar[r]% \ar[d]&\cdots\ar[d]\\ \cdots\ar[r]&0\ar[r]&R_{C}\ar[r]^{=}&R_{C}\ar[r]&0\ar[r]&\cdots}$ where $C\in\mathcal{C}$ and the rightmost copy of $R_{C}$ is in degree $n$. Let $J$ be the set of all $j_{C,n}$ for $C\in\mathcal{C}$ and $n\in\mathbb{Z}$.
Definition 2.2. A map $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ in $\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$ is a presheaf homology-isomorphism if $H_{n}(f)\colon H_{n}(X)\rightarrow H_{n}(Y)$ is an isomorphism, for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. A map $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ in $\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$ is a sheaf homology-isomorphism if the sheafification of the induced map on homology $L^{2}H_{n}(f)\colon L^{2}H_{n}(X)\rightarrow L^{2}H_{n}(Y)$ is an isomorphism, for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$.
Definition A.4. Let $E$ denote the class of all maps $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ such that $i_{a}(f)$ is injective and $s_{b}(f)$ is surjective, for all $a$ and $b$.
Definition 2.3. A map $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ in $\text{ch}(\mathcal{N})$ is a stalkwise homology-isomorphism if $(L^{2}f)_{p}$ is a homology-isomorphism of chain complexes of $R_{p}$-modules for all points $p$ in $\mathcal{E}$.
Definition 3.4. The unit interval complex, denoted $U$, consists of two copies of $R$ in degree 0, and one copy of $R$ in degree 1, the differential is the identity map on the first copy and minus the identity map on the second copy of $R$.
Definition 2.4. The localization of $\text{ch}(\mathcal{M})$ with respect to the class of all sheaf homology-isomorphisms is called the derived category of chain complexes of sheaves of $R$-modules on $\mathcal{C}$. It is denoted by $\mathcal{D}_{R}$.
Definition A.5. Let $E_{\sigma}$ denote the class of all $I$-cell complex pairs $X\rightarrow Y$ with $\sharp Y\leq\sigma$ such that $i_{a}(X)\rightarrow i_{a}(Y)$ is injective and $s_{b}(X)\rightarrow s_{b}(Y)$ is surjective, for all $a$ and $b$. Let $E^{\prime}$ denote the class of all $I$-cell complex pairs $X\rightarrow Y$ such that $i_{a}(X)\rightarrow i_{a}(Y)$ is injective and $s_{b}(X)\rightarrow s_{b}(Y)$ is surjective, for all $a$ and $b$. Let $E^{\prime\prime}$ denote the class of all relative $I$-cell complexes $X\rightarrow Y$ such that $i_{a}(X)\rightarrow i_{a}(Y)$ is injective and $s_{b}(X)\rightarrow s_{b}(Y)$ is surjective, for all $a$ and $b$.
Definition 4.5. A model category with a tensor product satisfies the monoid axiom if $j\otimes X$ is a weak equivalence for every acyclic cofibration $j$ and any object $X$, and if pushout and transfinite directed composition of such maps is again a weak equivalence [21].
Definition A.1. Let $X$ be an $I$-cell complex. The cardinality of the set of cells in $X$ is denoted $\sharp X$. Let $i\colon A\rightarrow X$ be a relative $I$-cell complex. The cardinality of the set of relative $I$-cells in the relative cell complex $i$ is denoted $\sharp(X,A)$.
Definition 4.3. A model category with a tensor product satisfies the pushout-product axiom if $M(f_{1},f_{2})$ is a cofibration whenever $f_{1}$ and $f_{2}$ are cofibrations, and $M(f_{1},f_{2})$ is an acyclic cofibration if $f_{1}$ or $f_{2}$ in addition is a weak equivalence.
Definition 7.2. A (weak) t-model category is a proper quasi-simplicial stable model category $\mathcal{K}$ with functorial factorizations equipped with a t-structure on its homotopy category together with a functorial factorization of maps in $\mathcal{K}$ into $n$-equivalences followed by co-$n$-equivalences, for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$.
Definition A.3. Let $\sigma$ be a cardinal number. We say that a functor $h$ from relative $I$-cell complexes to sets is $\sigma$-uniform if the cardinality of $h(X)$ is less or equal to $\sigma\times\sharp X$ for all $I$-cell complexes $X$.
Definition 5.1. A quasi-simplicial model category is a model category $\mathcal{K}$ that is a simplicial category (see [13, 9.1.2]) satisfying the axioms below. Map denotes the (based) simplicial mapping space, and $X\square S$ and $F_{\square}(S,X)$ are the tensor and cotensor of $X\in\mathcal{K}$ by a simplicial set $S$, respectively. weakM6: Let $\mathcal{S}$ be the category of simplicial sets. Let $X,Y$ be objects in $\mathcal{K}$ and let $S$ be an object in $\mathcal{S}$. There is a natural isomorphism of simplicial sets $\text{Map}(X\square S,Y)\cong\text{Map}(X,F_{\square}(S,X)).$ There is a natural isomorphism of sets $\mathcal{S}(S,\text{Map}(X,Y))\cong\mathcal{K}(X\square S,Y).$ M7: Let $i\colon A\rightarrow B$ be a cofibration in $\mathcal{K}$ and $f\colon X\rightarrow Y$ a fibration in $\mathcal{K}$. Then the map $i^{*}\times f_{*}\colon\text{Map}(B,X)\rightarrow\text{Map}(A,X)\times_{\text{% Map}(A,Y)}\text{Map}(B,Y)$ is a fibration of simplicial sets. If, in addition, $i$ or $f$ is a weak equivalence, then $i^{*}\times f_{*}$ is a weak equivalence.
Definition 6. The Day convolution symmetric monoidal $\infty$-category $\text{Fun}(\mathbf{C},\mathbf{D})^{\otimes}$ is the full subcategory of $\overline{\text{Fun}(\mathbf{C},\mathbf{D})^{\otimes}}$ whose objects are those corresponding to functors $F:\mathbf{C}^{\otimes}_{S}\to\mathbf{D}^{\otimes}_{S}$ which are in the essential image of the natural inclusion $\iota_{S}:\text{Fun}(\mathbf{C},\mathbf{D})^{S}\to\text{Fun}(\mathbf{C}^{S},% \mathbf{D}^{S})\cong\text{Fun}(\mathbf{C}^{\otimes}_{S},\mathbf{D}^{\otimes}_{% S}).$
Definition 1. A vacillating tableau $V_{\lambda}^{2n}$ of shape $\lambda$ and length $2n$ is a sequence $\lambda^{0},\lambda^{1},\dots,\lambda^{2n}$ of integer partitions such that (i) $\lambda^{0}=\emptyset$, and $\lambda^{2n}=\lambda$, (ii) $\lambda^{2i+1}$ is obtained from $\lambda^{2i}$ by doing nothing (i.e., $\lambda^{2i+1}=\lambda^{2i}$) or deleting a square, and (iii) $\lambda^{2i}$ is obtained from $\lambda^{2i-1}$ by doing nothing or adding a square.
Definition 9.1. A set with complicial identities is a simplicial set $X$, together with wedges $x\wedge_{i}y\in X_{m+1},$ defined when $x,y\in X_{m}$ and $\partial_{i}x=\partial_{i+1}y$, such that the following axioms hold. (1) If $x\wedge_{i}y$ is defined with $x,y\in X_{m}$, then $\displaystyle\partial_{j}(x\wedge_{i}y)=\partial_{j}x\wedge_{i-1}\partial_{j}y% \quad(0\leq j<i),$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}(x\wedge_{i}y)=y,$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i+2}(x\wedge_{i}y)=x,$ $\displaystyle\partial_{j}(x\wedge_{i}y)=\partial_{j-1}x\wedge_{i}\partial_{j-1% }y\quad(i+2<j\leq m+1).$ (2) If $x\in X_{m}$ and $0\leq i<m$ then $\epsilon_{i}x=\epsilon_{i}\partial_{i+1}x\wedge_{i}x,\quad\epsilon_{i+1}x=x% \wedge_{i}\epsilon_{i}\partial_{i}x.$ (3) If $A$ is of the form $b\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{i}z)$ then $A=(\partial_{i+2}b\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{i+1}\partial_{i+1}A.$ (4) If $A$ is of the form $(x\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{i+1}c$ then $A=\partial_{i+2}A\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{i}\partial_{i}c).$ (5) The equality $[x\wedge_{i}\partial_{i+1}(y\wedge_{i}z)]\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{i}z)=(x\wedge_{i}% y)\wedge_{i+1}[\partial_{i+1}(x\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{i}z]$ holds whenever either side is defined. (6) If $A$ is of the form $\partial_{i+2}[(x\wedge_{i+1}y)\wedge_{i+1}(y\wedge_{i}z)]$, then the equality $A\wedge_{i}(w\wedge_{i+1}\partial_{i}A)=(\partial_{i+3}A\wedge_{i}w)\wedge_{i+% 2}A$ holds whenever either side is defined. (7) If $i\leq j-3$ then the equality $(x\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{j}(z\wedge_{i}w)=(x\wedge_{j-1}z)\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{j-1% }w)$ holds whenever either side is defined.
Definition 5.3. Let $a$ be a $p$-dimensional basis element in a unital loop-free directed complex $K$. The the associated atom is the member $\langle a\rangle$ of $\nu K$ given by $\langle a\rangle=(\,(\partial^{-})^{p}a,(\partial^{+})^{p}a\mid\ldots\mid% \partial^{-}a,\partial^{+}a\mid a,a\mid 0,0\mid\ldots\,).$
Definition 4.1. Let $n$ and $k$ be integers with $0<k<n$. (1) An $(n-1)$-dimensional $k$-complicial horn in a stratified simplicial set is an $(n-1)$-dimensional $k$-horn $z=(z_{0},\ldots,z_{k-1},z_{k+1},\ldots,z_{n})$ such that $z_{i}$ is a $(k-1)$-complicial element for $0\leq i<k-1$ and is a $k$-complicial element for $k+1<i\leq n$. (2) An $n$-dimensional $k$-complicial element in a stratified simplicial set is a thin filler of an $(n-1)$-dimensional $k$-complicial horn.
Definition 2.4. The nerve of an $\omega$-category $C$ is the simplicial set $NC$ given by $N_{n}C=\operatorname{Hom}(\operatorname{\mathcal{O}}_{n},C)=\operatorname{Hom}% (\nu\Delta_{n},C).$
Definition 2.2. A free augmented directed complex is an augmented chain complex of free abelian groups concentrated in nonnegative dimensions, together with a prescribed basis for each chain complex. A morphism of free augmented directed complexes is an augmentation-preserving chain map which takes sums of basis elements to sums of basis elements.
Definition 3.2. A stratified simplicial set is a simplicial set together with a prescribed class of thin elements of positive dimension which includes the degenerate elements. A morphism of stratified simplicial sets is a morphism of simplicial sets taking thin elements to thin elements.
Definition 5.5. Let $a=[i_{0},\ldots,i_{p}]$ be a $p$-dimensional basis element in a simplex $\Delta_{n}$. Then a block in $a$ is a non-empty sequence of consecutive terms $\mathbf{u}=i_{r},i_{r+1},\ldots,i_{s}.$ A block is even if it has an even number of terms, it is odd if it has an odd number of terms, it is initial if it includes $i_{0}$, and it is final if it includes $i_{p}$.
Definition 4.2. A complicial set is a stratified simplicial set satisfying the following conditions. (1) Every thin $1$-dimensional element is degenerate. (2) For $0<k<n$ every $(n-1)$-dimensional $k$-complicial horn has a unique thin filler. (3) For $0<k<n$, if $x$ is an $n$-dimensional $k$-complicial element and if $\partial_{k-1}x$ and $\partial_{k+1}x$ are thin, then $\partial_{k}x$ is thin.
Definition 5.2. A free augmented directed complex is unital if $\epsilon(\partial^{-})^{p}a=\epsilon(\partial^{+})^{p}a=1$ for every basis element $a$, where $p$ is the dimension of $a$. A free augmented directed complex is loop-free if the transitive closure of the relation $<$ is a strict partial order on its basis elements.
Definition 3.1. Let $C$ be an $\omega$-category. Then the thin elements in $NC$ are the elements $x$ in $N_{n}C$ with $n>0$ such that $d_{n-1}^{-}xu=d_{n-1}^{+}xu=xu$ for all $u\in\nu\Delta_{n}$
Definition 3.6. We call a DG functor $\Phi:{\mathcal{A}}\to{\mathcal{B}}$ between small DG categories a localization if the functor $\Phi^{*}:\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{A}})\to\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{B}})$ is a localization up to direct summands.
Definition 6.1. ([R])Let ${\mathcal{T}}$ be a small triangulated category and $E\in{\mathcal{T}}$ an object. Take the sequence $\{{\mathcal{T}}_{n}\}_{n\geq 0}$ of full subcategories of ${\mathcal{T}},$ where - ${\mathcal{T}}_{0}$ consists of direct summands of finite direct sums of shifts of $E;$ - ${\mathcal{T}}_{n+1}$ consists of direct summands of objects $F$ such that there exists an exact triangle $F^{\prime}\to F\to F^{\prime\prime}\to F^{\prime}[1]$ with $F^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{T}}_{n},$ $F^{\prime\prime}\in{\mathcal{T}}_{0}.$ We call $E$ a strong generator if for $n>>0$ one has ${\mathcal{T}}_{n}={\mathcal{T}}.$
Definition 2.6. A small DG category ${\mathcal{A}}$ is homotopically finitely presented (hfp) if in the homotopy category $\operatorname{Ho}_{M}(dgcat_{k})$ ${\mathcal{A}}$ is a retract of a finite cellular DG category.
Definition 2.2. A DG algebra $A$ is homotopically finitely presented (hfp), if in the homotopy category $\operatorname{Ho}(dgalg_{k})$ $A$ is a retract of some finite cellular DG algebra $B.$ Equivalently, $A$ is a homotopically compact object of $dgalg_{k}.$
Definition 4.7. Suppose that we are given a pair of DG functors between small DG categories ${\mathcal{A}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle F_{1}}}{{\leftarrow}}{\mathcal{C}}% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle F_{2}}}{{\to}}{\mathcal{B}}.$ Take the bimodule $M:=N_{F_{1}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle{\mathbf{L}}}}{{\otimes}}_{{\mathcal{C}}}N_% {F_{2}^{op}},$ where the derived tensor product is computed via bar resolution. We put ${\mathcal{A}}\sqcup_{({\mathcal{C}})}{\mathcal{B}}:={\mathcal{A}}\sqcup_{M}{% \mathcal{B}},\quad{\mathcal{A}}\times_{({\mathcal{C}})}{\mathcal{B}}:={% \mathcal{A}}\times_{M}{\mathcal{B}}.$
Definition 2.3. 1) A DG algebra $A$ is smooth over $k$ if the diagonal bimodule is perfect: $A\in\operatorname{Perf}(A\otimes A^{op}).$ 2) A DG algebra $A$ is proper over $k$ if $A\in\operatorname{Perf}(k),$ or, in other words the cohomology of $A$ is finite-dimensional.
Definition 1.7. We say that a DG category ${\mathcal{A}}$ admits a smooth categorical compactification if there is a DG quasi-functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ such that the DG category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is smooth and proper, the functor $F^{*}:\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{C}})\to\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{A}})$ is a localization (up to direct summands), and its kernel is generated by one object.
Definition 3.2. A DG functor $\Phi:{\mathcal{A}}\to{\mathcal{B}}$ between small DG categories is called a homological epimorphism if the extension of scalars functor $\Phi^{*}:D({\mathcal{A}})\to D({\mathcal{B}})$ is a localization.
Definition 1.1. 1) A small DG category ${\mathcal{C}}$ over $k$ is smooth if the diagonal ${\mathcal{C}}$-bimodule is perfect. 2) ${\mathcal{C}}$ is called proper if for $X,Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$ the complex $\operatorname{Hom}(X,Y)$ is perfect over $k.$
Definition 1.3. 1) A DG algebra $A$ is homotopically finitely presented (hfp) if in the homotopy category of DG algebras it is a retract of a free graded algebra $k\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\rangle$ with differential satisfying $dx_{i}\in k\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{i-1}\rangle.$ 2) A small DG category is hfp if it is Morita equivalent to a DG algebra which is hfp.
Definition 2.1. A finite cellular DG algebra $B$ is a DG algebra which as a graded algebra is isomorphic to the free algebra of finite type: $B^{gr}\cong k\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\rangle,$ and moreover we have $dx_{i}\in k\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{i-1}\rangle,\quad 1\leq i\leq n.$
Definition 5.1. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be an exact category with exact small coproducts. Denote by $K({\mathcal{C}})$ the homotopy category of complexes of objects in ${\mathcal{C}}.$ Define the subcategory of coacyclic complexes $\text{co-Acycl}({\mathcal{C}})\subset K({\mathcal{C}})$ to be the localizing subcategory generated by totalizations of short exact triples of complexes. Then the coderived category is defined as a quootient: $D^{co}({\mathcal{C}}):=K({\mathcal{C}})/\text{co-Acycl}({\mathcal{C}}).$
Definition 2.5. A DG category ${\mathcal{B}}$ is called finite cellular if it has a finite number of objects, as a graded category is freely generated by a finite number of morphisms $f_{1},\dots,f_{n},$ and we have $df_{i}\in k\langle f_{1},\dots f_{i-1}\rangle,\quad 1\leq i\leq n.$
Definition 7.10. Let $X\to Y$ be a proper morphism. A closed subscheme $S\subset Y$ is called a non-rational center of $Y$ with respect to $f$ if the natural morphism $I_{S}\to{\mathbf{R}}f_{*}I_{f^{-1}(S)}$ is an isomorphism in $D^{b}_{coh}(Y).$.
Definition 2.10. We say that a DG category ${\mathcal{A}}$ admits a smooth categorical compactification if there is a DG quasi-functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{A}}$ such that the DG category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is smooth and proper, the functor $F^{*}:\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{C}})\to\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{A}})$ is a localization (up to direct summands), and its kernel is generated by one object.
Definition 6.9. 1) A nice ringed space over $k$ is a pair $(S,{\mathcal{A}}_{S})$ consisting of a Noetherian separated $k$-scheme $S$ and a coherent sheaf of ${\mathcal{O}}_{S}$-algebras ${\mathcal{A}}_{S},$ satisfying the following property: - there is a nilpotent coherent two-sided ideal sheaf $I\subset{\mathcal{A}}_{S},$ such that there is an isomorphism of ${\mathcal{O}}_{S}$-algebras: ${\mathcal{A}}_{S}/I\cong\bigoplus\limits_{i=1}^{n}{\mathcal{O}}_{S}/J_{i},$ where $J_{i}\subset{\mathcal{O}}_{S}$ are some coherent ideal sheaves. 2) A morphism of nice ringed spaces from $(S,{\mathcal{A}}_{S})$ to $(S^{\prime},{\mathcal{A}}_{S^{\prime}})$ is a pair $(f,\varphi),$ where $f:S\to S^{\prime}$ is a morphism of schemes and $\varphi:f^{*}{\mathcal{A}}_{Y}\to{\mathcal{A}}_{S}$ is a (possibly non-unital) morphism of ${\mathcal{O}}_{S}$-algebras.
Definition A.1. 1) An exact category ${\mathcal{A}}$ is called a Frobenious category if it has enough injective objects, enough projective objects, and these two classes of objects coincide. 2) If ${\mathcal{A}}$ is a Frobenious exact category, its stable triangulated category $\underline{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is defined as follows. First, $Ob(\underline{{\mathcal{A}}})=Ob({\mathcal{A}}).$ Further, for $X,Y\in{\mathcal{A}}$ the abelian group of morphisms $\operatorname{Hom}_{\underline{{\mathcal{A}}}}(X,Y)$ is defined as the quotient of $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{A}}}(X,Y)$ by the subgroup of morphisms which are compositions $X\to I\to Y$ for some projective-injective object $I\in{\mathcal{A}}.$ The composition is induced by that in ${\mathcal{A}}.$ The shift functor is defined by choosing a conflation $0\to X\to I\to X[1]\to 0,$ for each $X\in Ob(\underline{{\mathcal{A}}}).$ Further, each triangle is isomorphic to a standard one $(\bar{i},\bar{p},\bar{e}),$ given by a morphism of conflation $(i,p)$ $\begin{CD}0@>{}>{}>X@>{i}>{}>Y@>{p}>{}>Z@>{}>{}>0\\ @V{\operatorname{id}}V{}V@V{}V{}V@V{e}V{}V\\ 0@>{}>{}>X@>{}>{}>I@>{}>{}>X[1]@>{}>{}>0.\end{CD}$
Definition 4.1. Let ${\mathcal{A}}$ and ${\mathcal{B}}$ be small DG categories, and $M\in D({\mathcal{A}}\otimes{\mathcal{B}}^{op})$ a bimodule. Define the DG category ${\mathcal{C}}={\mathcal{A}}\sqcup_{M}{\mathcal{B}}$ as follows. First, $Ob({\mathcal{A}}\sqcup_{M}{\mathcal{B}})=Ob({\mathcal{A}})\sqcup Ob({\mathcal{% B}}).$ For $X_{1},X_{2}$ we put $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(X_{1},X_{2})=\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{% A}}}(X_{1},X_{2}).$ Similarly, for $Y_{1},Y_{2}\in{\mathcal{B}}$ we put $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(X_{1},X_{2})=\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{% B}}}(Y_{1},Y_{2}).$ Further, we put $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(X_{1},Y_{1})=M(X_{1},Y_{1}),$ $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(Y_{1},X_{1})=0.$ The differential and the composition are obvious. Also, we define the category ${\mathcal{A}}\times_{M}{\mathcal{B}}$ to be pre-triangulated envelope of ${\mathcal{A}}\sqcup_{M}{\mathcal{B}}.$
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category. A $t$-structure on $\mathcal{T}$ is a pair of full subcategories $(\mathcal{D}^{\leq{0}},\mathcal{D}^{\geq{0}})$ which satisfies the properties (tS1)â€“(tS3) below. Here we use the customary notation that $\mathcal{D}^{\leq{n}}=\Sigma^{-n}\mathcal{D}^{\leq{0}}$ and $\mathcal{D}^{\geq{n}}=\Sigma^{-n}\mathcal{D}^{\geq{0}}$ for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. (tS1) $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(A,B)=0$ for all $A\in\mathcal{D}^{\leq{0}}$ and $B\in\mathcal{D}^{\geq{1}}$. (tS2) $\mathcal{D}^{\leq{0}}\subseteq\mathcal{D}^{\leq{1}}$ and $\mathcal{D}^{\geq{0}}\supseteq\mathcal{D}^{\geq{1}}$. (tS3) For every object $X\in\mathcal{T}$ there exist a triangle $\tau^{\leq{0}}X\longrightarrow X\longrightarrow\tau^{\geq{1}}X\longrightarrow% \Sigma\tau^{\leq{0}}X.$ The heart of the $t$-structure is the full subcategory $\mathcal{G}=\mathcal{D}^{\leq{0}}\cap\mathcal{D}^{\geq{0}}$ of $\mathcal{T}$.
Definition 5.11 ([Gro12]). A derivator $\mathbb{D}$ is pointed if: (Der6) The category $\mathbb{D}(\mathds{1})$ is pointed (cf. Definition 3.3). A pointed derivator is called stable if: (Der7) The full subcategory of $\mathbb{D}([1]\times[1])$ consisting cartesian squares in the sense of [Gro12, Definition 3.9] coincides with the full subcategory of cocartesian squares.
